  Top Del. court upholds dismissal of forged art lawsuit

By RANDALL CHASE, Associated Press
Posted Friday, April 27, 2007 at 11:36 am

DOVER ? The state Supreme Court has upheld the dismissal of lawsuit 
filed by a Delaware couple who claimed they were defrauded when they 
bought a forged painting at a Christie?s auction.

Johannes and Betty Krahmer appealed to the Supreme Court last year after 
a Chancery Court judge dismissed their 2004 lawsuit against Christie?s, 
saying the lawsuit was filed too late, and that there was no evidence to 
infer that the famed auction house knew the painting was a fake.

After hearing oral arguments last month, the Supreme Court issued a 
two-paragraph order Wednesday upholding the lower court decision.

Betty Krahmer declined to comment on the ruling Friday. Wilmington 
attorney Victor Battaglia, who represented the couple, was not 
immediately available for comment.
Court arguments centered on whether Delaware?s ?time of discovery? rule, 
which allows the filing period for a lawsuit to begin when a person 
first believes he has been injured, rather than the date of actual 
injury, applied to the Krahmers.

Christie?s argued that the rule typically applies to services provided 
by professionals such as doctors, lawyers and accountants, not to the 
purchase of goods.

Battaglia argued that fine art was different from other consumer goods, 
and that the case involved both an ?inherently unknowable? injury and a 
?blamelessly ignorant? plaintiff, the two criteria required by the time 
of discovery rule.

Battaglia said that, unlike art professionals, the Krahmers had no 
reason to suspect that the painting might be a fake, and that Christie?s 
representatives were so enthralled with the painting?s purported lineage 
that they failed to do their homework.

The dispute involved an oil portrait of a woman that the Krahmers bought 
in 1986, thinking it was the 1912 work ?Interior? by American 
impressionist Frank Weston Benson. They paid $38,500 and received a 
six-year limited warranty of authenticity.

In 1999, the Krahmers contacted a committee in Boston compiling a 
definitive list of Benson?s works. They subsequently learned of a 
similar painting at a Connecticut museum, which turned out to be the 
real one. When the Krahmers tried to sell their painting on consignment 
in 2002 to Sotheby?s auction house, they were told by a Sotheby?s 
restorer that it might be a forgery.

The committee in Boston theorized that the original was acquired from 
Benson by the famed Detroit Club in Michigan in 1914, but was sold in 
the early 1970s and replaced with a copy, perhaps in the original frame.

The Krahmers asked Christie?s to rescind the 1986 sale, but the auction 
house refused, saying the six-year warranty of authenticity had expired.

http://www.delawareonline.com/




