SoCal man indicted for transporting stolen violins to Europe

ASSOCIATED PRESS
6:22 p.m. April 25, 2007
LOS ANGELES ? A man was indicted Wednesday on charges of transporting 
two rare, stolen violins worth more than $300,000 from Los Angeles to 
Paris in an attempt to sell them.

Anthony Eugene Notarstefano, 43, of Long Beach was charged with 
possession and foreign transportation of stolen goods. He faces up to 20 
years in federal prison if convicted.

Notarstefano was arrested last month by French police after authorities 
said he approached the owner of a Paris violin shop with an offer to 
sell the two instruments for $65,000.

In a federal affidavit filed after his arrest, investigators said the 
violins were stolen Dec. 23 from the home of Los Angeles Philharmonic 
violinist Mark Kashper. One was crafted in the 18th century by Carlo 
Tononi, and the other was made in the 19th century by Jean-Baptiste 
Vuillaume.

Notarstefano remains in French custody while awaiting trial there in 
connection to the case, said Thom Mrozek, a U.S. Attorney's spokesman.

He will be extradited to face charges in the U.S. upon completion of the 
French case, Mrozek said.

It was not immediately known whether Notarstefano had hired an attorney 
to represent him in Los Angeles.

http://www.signonsandiego.com/




